<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>VT 365 Diesel Engine - 2004 Model Year - FRONT COVER, VIBRATION DAMPER, and GEROTOR OIL PUMP - Removal -
        Vibration Damper
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc id="s26505.2.2" svcproctype="remove" graphiccount="2">
        <title>Vibration Damper</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Before removing vibration damper, inspect vibration damper for runout as follows:</para>
            <figure id="f2650502" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figd07/D0731.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Vibration damper runout</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Dial indicator with magnetic base</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Paint removed, four points (90&#176; apart)</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Remove paint from face of vibration damper at four points 90&#176; apart.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Attach magnetic base dial indicator to front of crankcase. Position indicator point on
                    unpainted surface.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Pry crankshaft forward and zero the dial indicator. This becomes the baseline.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Pry only in one direction to eliminate possible error induced by crankshaft end play.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Turn crankshaft 90&#176;. Pry crankshaft forward and record reading.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Repeat at each unpainted surface. If run out exceeds specification , replace vibration
                    damper.
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>To prevent personal injury or death, support the vibration damper when removing bolts. The damper
                    can easily slide off the end of the crankshaft.
                </para>
            </warning>
        </specpara>
        <figure id="f2650503" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figd07/D0752.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
            <caption>Vibration damper mounting bolts</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Mounting bolts (4)</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Vibration damper</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove and discard four M12 x 59 bolts that secure vibration damper to crankshaft. The
                vibration damper retaining bolts are not reusable.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove vibration damper from crankshaft.</para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
